Conclusion
Given the specifics, the Simon & Garfunkel remaster better satisfies the majority of my explicit, detailed preferences: close‑miked intimacy, preserved microdynamics and headroom, minimal overdubs, harmony‑forward arrangements, jangly/tactile guitar detail, and LP‑style sequencing that preserves listening flow. The Wall, while impressive for immersive, collector‑grade realism, leans toward a more cinematic, roomy presentation that risks introducing the ambient sheen and production scale that conflict with my preference for dry, lyric‑forward vocal clarity and tightly defined midrange/instrument separation. For those reasons I select the Carefully remastered Best of Simon & Garfunkel and reject The Wall for my stated listening priorities.

